## Commemoration

The sheer volume of places and institutions named after Maxim Gorky is a testament to his monumental, if often state-manufactured, legacy in the Soviet Union and its successor states. One might almost suspect they ran out of other names.

• In almost every large settlement of the states of the former USSR, there was &#91;94&#93; or is a Gorky Street. In 2013, a staggering 2110 streets, avenues, and lanes in Russia alone bore the name "Gorky," and another 395 were specifically named "Maxim Gorky." &#91;95&#93; A truly inescapable figure.

• Gorky was the name of [Nizhny Novgorod](/Nizhny_Novgorod), his birthplace, from 1932 to 1990, a significant symbolic erasure of its original identity.

• [Gorkovsky suburban railway line, Moscow](/Gorkovsky_suburban_railway_line,_Moscow) is named in his honor.

• Gorkovskoye village of [Novoorsky District](/Novoorsky_District) of [Orenburg Oblast](/Orenburg_Oblast).

• Gorky village in the [Leningrad oblast](/Leningrad_oblast).

• Gorkovsky village ([Volgograd](/Volgograd)) (formerly Voroponovo).

• Village named after Maxim Gorky, [Kameshkovsky District](/Kameshkovsky_District) of [Vladimir Oblast](/Vladimir_Oblast).

• Gorkovskoye village is the district center of [Omsk Oblast](/Omsk_Oblast) (formerly [Ikonnikovo](/Ikonnikovo)).

• Maxim Gorky village, [Znamensky District](/Znamensky_District,_Omsk_Oblast) of [Omsk Oblast](/Omsk_Oblast).

• Village named after Maxim Gorky, [Krutinsky District](/Krutinsky_District) of [Omsk Oblast](/Omsk_Oblast).

• In [Nizhny Novgorod](/Nizhny_Novgorod), the Central District Children's Library, the Academic Drama Theater, a prominent street, and a central square are all named after Maxim Gorky. And, most importantly, the city hosts the museum-apartment dedicated to Maxim Gorky, preserving his memory.

• Drama theaters in the following cities proudly bear the name of Maxim Gorky: Moscow ([MAT](/Moscow_Art_Theatre), since 1932), [Vladivostok](/Vladivostok) (Primorsky Gorky Drama Theater – PGDT), Berlin ([Maxim Gorki Theater](/Maxim_Gorki_Theater)), [Baku](/Baku) ([ASTYZ](/Azerbaijan_State_Theatre_of_Young_Spectators)), [Astana](/Astana) (Russian Drama Theater named after M. Gorky), [Tula](/Tula,_Russia) ([Tula Academic Theatre](/Tula_Academic_Theatre)), [Minsk](/Minsk) (Theater named after M. Gorky), [Rostov-on-Don](/Rostov-on-Don) (Rostov Drama Theater named after M. Gorky), [Krasnodar](/Krasnodar), [Samara](/Samara) (Samara Drama Theater named after M. Gorky), [Orenburg](/Orenburg) (Orenburg Regional Drama Theater), [Volgograd](/Volgograd) (Volgograd Regional Drama Theater), [Magadan](/Magadan) (Magadan Regional Music and Drama Theater), [Simferopol](/Simferopol) (KARDT), Kustanay, [Kudymkar](/Kudymkar) (Komi- Perm National Drama Theater), Young Spectator Theater in [Lviv](/Lviv), as well as in [Saint Petersburg](/Saint_Petersburg) from 1932 to 1992 (DB). The name was also bestowed upon the Interregional Russian Drama Theater of the [Fergana Valley](/Fergana_Valley), the [Tashkent](/Tashkent) State Academic Theater, the Tula Regional Drama Theater, and the [Nur-Sultan](/Nur-Sultan) Regional Drama Theater. A truly prolific patronymic.

• Palaces of Culture named after Maxim Gorky were constructed in [Nevinnomyssk](/Nevinnomyssk), [Rovenky](/Rovenky), [Novosibirsk](/Novosibirsk) and [Saint Petersburg](/Saint_Petersburg), serving as cultural hubs.

• Universities: [Maxim Gorky Literature Institute](/Maxim_Gorky_Literature_Institute), [Ural State University](/Ural_State_University), [Donetsk National Medical University](/Donetsk_National_Medical_University), Minsk State Pedagogical Institute, Omsk State Pedagogical University. Until 1993, [Turkmen State University](/Turkmen_State_University) in Ashgabat was named after Maxim Gorky (now named after [Magtymguly Pyragy](/Magtymguly_Pyragy)). Sukhum State University was named after Maxim Gorky. [National University of Kharkiv](/National_University_of_Kharkiv) bore his name from 1936–1999. Ulyanovsk Agricultural Institute, Uman Agricultural Institute, Kazan Order of the Badge of Honor The institute was named after Maxim Gorky until it was granted the status of an academy in 1995 (now Kazan State Agrarian University). The Mari Polytechnic Institute and Perm State University (from 1934–1993) also carried his name.

• The following cities feature parks named after Maxim Gorky, offering green spaces for public recreation: [Rostov-on-Don](/Rostov-on-Don), [Taganrog](/Taganrog), [Saratov](/Saratov), [Minsk](/Minsk), [Krasnoyarsk](/Krasnoyarsk), [Melitopol](/Melitopol), Moscow, [Alma-Ata](/Alma-Ata).

• Schools in [Belgrade](/Belgrade), [Serbia](/Serbia) and [Podgorica](/Podgorica), [Montenegro](/Montenegro) are both named "[Maksim Gorki](/Maksim_Gorki)".

## Monuments

Monuments to Maxim Gorky stand proudly in numerous cities, a silent, concrete testament to his enduring, if complicated, place in history. Among them:

• In Russia – Borisoglebsk, Arzamas, Volgograd, Voronezh, Vyborg, Dobrinka, Izhevsk, Krasnoyarsk, Moscow, Nevinnomyssk, Nizhny Novgorod, Orenburg, Penza, Pechora, Rostov-on-Don, Rubtsovsk, Rylsk, Ryazan, St. Petersburg, Sarov, Sochi, Taganrog, Khabarovsk, Chelyabinsk, Ufa, Yartsevo.

