## Numismatics

Silver commemorative coin, 2 rubles "Maxim Gorky", 2018

Maxim Gorky's image has also been immortalized on coinage, further cementing his status as a national icon.

• In 1988, a 1 ruble coin was issued in the USSR, commemorating the 120th anniversary of the writer's birth.

• In 2018, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of his birthday, the [Bank of Russia](/Bank_of_Russia) issued a commemorative silver coin with a face value of 2 rubles within its esteemed "Outstanding Personalities of Russia" series.

## Depictions and adaptations

Maxim Gorky's powerful narratives and dramatic works have provided fertile ground for numerous adaptations across various artistic mediums, demonstrating the enduring resonance of his stories.

• In 1912, the Italian composer [Giacomo Orefice](/Giacomo_Orefice) drew inspiration from Gorky's 1892 short story *[Makar Chudra](/Makar_Chudra)*, basing his opera *Radda* on the titular character.

• In 1932, the influential German playwright [Bertolt Brecht](/Bertolt_Brecht) published his renowned play *[The Mother](/The_Mother_(Brecht_play))*, a significant adaptation directly based on Gorky's 1906 novel *[Mother](/Mother_(Gorky_novel))*. The same seminal novel also served as the source material for an opera by [Valery Zhelobinsky](/Valery_Viktorovich_Zhelobinsky) in 1938.

• Between 1938 and 1939, Gorky's acclaimed three-part autobiography was brought to the silver screen by [Soyuzdetfilm](/Soyuzdetfilm) as a trilogy of feature films: *[The Childhood of Maxim Gorky](/The_Childhood_of_Maxim_Gorky)*, *[My Apprenticeship](/Gorky_2:_My_Apprenticeship)*, and *[My Universities](/Gorky_3:_My_Universities)*. All three were skillfully directed by [Mark Donskoy](/Mark_Donskoy), creating a cinematic classic.

• In 1975, Gorky's 1908 play *[The Last Ones](/The_Last_Ones)* (Последние), made its New York debut at the [Manhattan Theater Club](/Manhattan_Theater_Club), presented under the alternative English title *Our Father*. The production was directed by [Keith Fowler](/Keith_Fowler), introducing Gorky's work to a new American audience.

• In 1985, Gorky's 1906 play *[Enemies](/Enemies_(play))*, translated by Kitty Hunter-Blair and Jeremy Brooks, was directed in London by Ann Pennington in association with the [Internationalist Theatre](/Internationalist_Theatre). This production notably coincided with the tail end of the [British miners' strike of 1984–1985](/UK_miners%27_strike_(1984%E2%80%9385)). Critics observed that Gorky's "pseudo-populism" was effectively stripped away in this staging, with the actors speaking "without distinctive accents and consequently without populist sentiment," allowing the raw themes to emerge. &#91;101&#93;

• Drawing profoundly from Maxim Gorky's celebrated novel *Mother*, the silent film *[Mother (1926 film)](/Mother_(1926_film))*, directed by the visionary [Vsevolod Pudovkin](/Vsevolod_Pudovkin), was crafted with profound artistry, becoming a landmark of early Soviet cinema.

